    "## 3. Loading the Dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why Do We Load Data This Way?\n",
    "\n",
    "We use `pd.read_csv()` to load comma-separated value files directly into a pandas DataFrame. A DataFrame is a two-dimensional labeled data structure — think of it as an Excel table inside Python. It has rows and columns, each with labels.\n",
    "\n",
    "### What Happens if the Dataset Path is Wrong?\n",
    "\n",
    "Python will raise a `FileNotFoundError`. This is one of the most common beginner mistakes. Always ensure:\n",
    "1. The file name is spelled correctly (case-sensitive on Linux/Mac).\n",
    "2. The file is in the same directory as the notebook, OR you provide the full absolute path.\n",
    "3. The file extension is correct (.csv, not .CSV or .xlsx).\n",
    "\n",
    "### Common File Loading Errors:\n",
    "- `FileNotFoundError`: File does not exist at the specified path.\n",
    "- `UnicodeDecodeError`: The file uses a different character encoding (try `encoding='latin-1'` or `encoding='utf-8-sig'`).\n",
    "- `ParserError`: The file is malformed (e.g., inconsistent number of columns in some rows)."
